                        <td>
                        <font class = headline>The Importance of Raid Preparation (Part 4)</font><br>
                        <IMG
                            SRC="Not Used"
                            BORDER="0"
                            ALIGN="RIGHT" HSPACE="20" VSPACE="10">
                       <font size = 2 face = arial color = black>Posted by: necrro</font><br> 
                       <font size = 1 face = arial color = black>Posted on: Mon Jul  1 21:39:53 2002</font><br><br> 
                       3. Plan of Attack<br><br>You must have a plan on how you will approach your objective. Many a raid has failed even though it has sufficient numbers, levels and classes because the plan of attack is wrong or not executed. Simply read the EQ boards to hear of failed Naggy raids that started with a Bum rush or failed Avatar of War raids that resulted from the failure of clerics and Main tanks to communicate on healing and when to do disciplines, etc. (I will try to stay away from really high end stuff to keep it simple).<br><br>Are you going to sneak up there or waste the place as you march towards your destination? If you are sneaking, is everyone invised? If not, does everyone have a back up invis plan? Are you aware that one good Bard with invis song playing (it never fails) can march a full group up into Castle Mistmoore and raid any room they want pretty much without dealing with any yard trash on the way. If you are doing Kedge, has everyone spent the extra 10pp to have an emergency EB potion on their person (these do not poof if LD whereas waterstones or other summoned items do).<br><br>How will your groups advance? Group A or 1 should always have the main puller and main assist if possible. Additionally, those do not have to be and often are not the same person. Make sure your clerics have Hot Buttons for Healing that do 2 things: trigger the correct heal spell and do a raid channel message saying they are healing (%T). That way people stay coordinated. The same is true for your puller although most pullers do this anyway.<br><br>Make sure groups know their roles. Some groups may hold back and unleash nukes at 50% hp, some may solely be for heals, some may be positioned behind a mob (if big enough to matter).<br><br>Make sure your puller knows the pull spot and where and when to pull.<br><br>4. Loot<br><br>Last, but not least, make sure everyone knows the loot rules. Tell the raiders who is to get the peice of loot and that noone else loots. If a raid happens and someone loots a no drop quest item, imagine the carnage. If it is a big raid with lots of loot, deisgnate a main looter. Clarify, if required, whether yard trash and other superfluous kills are FFA (usually they are) (e.g. - Killing bugs and kobolds on the way up to Naggy or the Efreeti camp).<br><br><br>Conclusion<br><br>Whatever you do, the planning is the key to a successful raid. Try to eliminate downtime and wasted time spent bikcering or clearing the raid channel. The most succesful raids do not take all day and allow the players to leave the raid and spend some time playing on their own that day. They are taking their time out to help you, try not to take all their time.<br><br> 
                       Necrro 53rd Heretic (Misty Knight)<br>
                       <img src = "/beta/_necrro/_necrro/portrait.gif

